{
    "level": "A1–A2",
    "intro": "In this topic you will collect the most important <strong>irregular plurals</strong> — plural forms that cannot be built just with <strong>-s</strong> or <strong>-es</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "VOWEL CHANGE",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Some words form the plural by changing a vowel inside the word.",
            "example": "man → men, foot → feet"
        },
        {
            "label": "SPECIAL ENDING",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "Some words have a special ending that you simply need to remember.",
            "example": "child → children, person → people"
        },
        {
            "label": "SAME FORM",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "Some nouns look the same in singular and plural.",
            "example": "sheep → sheep, deer → deer"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. The most important forms",
    "intro": "Start with the most common irregular plurals.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "People",
            "title": "man → men / woman → women / person → people",
            "subtitle": "people"
        },
        {
            "label": "Family",
            "title": "child → children",
            "subtitle": "a special -ren form"
        },
        {
            "label": "Body",
            "title": "foot → feet / tooth → teeth",
            "subtitle": "body parts"
        },
        {
            "label": "Animals",
            "title": "mouse → mice / sheep → sheep / deer → deer",
            "subtitle": "a changed form or the same form"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. Main types of irregular plurals",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Vowel change",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "In these words, the middle of the word changes, not just the ending.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "man → men",
                    "ua": "man → men"
                },
                {
                    "en": "woman → women",
                    "ua": "woman → women"
                },
                {
                    "en": "foot → feet",
                    "ua": "foot → feet"
                },
                {
                    "en": "tooth → teeth",
                    "ua": "tooth → teeth"
                },
                {
                    "en": "mouse → mice",
                    "ua": "mouse → mice"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Special form",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "Some words have a plural that does not follow a regular pattern, so you have to remember it separately.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "child → children",
                    "ua": "child → children"
                },
                {
                    "en": "person → people",
                    "ua": "person → people"
                },
                {
                    "en": "ox → oxen",
                    "ua": "ox → oxen"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Same form",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Some words use the same form in singular and plural. The number comes from the context or the number word.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "one sheep / two sheep",
                    "ua": "one sheep / two sheep"
                },
                {
                    "en": "one deer / three deer",
                    "ua": "one deer / three deer"
                },
                {
                    "en": "This fish is small. / These fish are small.",
                    "ua": "This fish is small. / These fish are small."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Quick table",
    "intro": "Save the most useful pairs as ready chunks.",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "man → men",
            "ua": "woman → women",
            "note": "people"
        },
        {
            "en": "child → children",
            "ua": "person → people",
            "note": "common exceptions"
        },
        {
            "en": "foot → feet",
            "ua": "tooth → teeth",
            "note": "body parts"
        },
        {
            "en": "mouse → mice",
            "ua": "goose → geese",
            "note": "vowel change"
        },
        {
            "en": "sheep → sheep",
            "ua": "deer → deer",
            "note": "same form"
        }
    ],
    "warning": "Do not try to build these forms with a regular plural rule. It is better to learn them in pairs."
}

{
    "title": "4. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using a regular plural instead of an irregular form.",
            "wrong": "mans / womans / childs",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">men / women / children</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Adding -s to same-form nouns.",
            "wrong": "sheeps / deers",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">sheep / deer</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Using persons instead of people in a basic meaning.",
            "wrong": "There are five persons in the room.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">There are five people in the room.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "5. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Irregular plurals</strong> do not use a simple <strong>-s</strong> ending.",
        "The most important forms are <strong>man → men</strong>, <strong>woman → women</strong>, <strong>child → children</strong>, and <strong>person → people</strong>.",
        "Other common examples are <strong>foot → feet</strong>, <strong>tooth → teeth</strong>, and <strong>mouse → mice</strong>.",
        "Some nouns do not change in the plural: <strong>sheep</strong>, <strong>deer</strong>, and sometimes <strong>fish</strong>.",
        "The best strategy is to learn irregular forms in pairs and use them in short sentences."
    ]
}

